Problem 1 - Remarks on Problem Solving: He understood the problem and explained his approach. But then again, it was hard to understand his approach. I tried multiple times to understand what he was saying, by asking follow up questions but that ended up taking a lot more time coz he wouldn't have patience to listen till I finished asking the question, and secondly he would keep repeating his sentences several times. past 15 mins, I asked him to stop explaining and start writing code. This time I did not want him to waste time on explaining things that was difficult to understand so I asked him to start writing code, right after explaining the high-level of his approach.
Problem 2- Remarks on Code Implementatio:
Unfortunately his code was nowhere near the optimal solution of using Dijkstra's algorithm. His code was more like a BFS traversal, treated it as an unweighted graph, used FIFO for addressing priority (rather than min-heap), incorrect indexing while relaxing an edge, no optimisation for visited nodes, etc,. I could go on over the list of errors forever.
Code had a lot of issues.
Remarks on DSA Theory: He gave the right answer but it took him a lot of time to think + his explanation was extremely difficult to understand. Also whenever I would ask a follow-up question, he wouldn't listen to it carefully and end up giving a completely different answer. On top of it, he kept on repeating his sentences over and over again. He was also impatient to wait until I finished a question. At times he won't even know that both of us were talking about the same thing, coz he won't understand what question did I ask - this would again take a couple more mins. I gave him warnings from time to time to listen me carefully but it didn't work.
Remarks on Core CS Theory: It was difficult to foolow his answer mid way through so I'm giving partial credits for telling me correct answer for the 1st half.
Overall Comments: Candidate needs to practice coding to be able to come up with optimal solution in an interview. I would also highly suggest him to work on his communication skills and limit himself to 5-8 mins while explaining his appraoch and save 10-15 mins for writing the code (and not the other way around).
